05273nam a22008055i 9781400880782DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2016    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008807827 a10.1515/97814008807822doi  a(DE-B1597)468086  a(OCoLC)946038875  a(OCoLC)949750768  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC385b.K25 2016 7aHIS0370102bisacsh 7aPOL0100002bisacsh 7aREL0670002bisacsh1 aKantorowicz, Ernst, eauthor.14aThe King's Two Bodies :bA Study in Medieval Political Theology /cErnst Kantorowicz. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource :b32 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Classics ;v2200tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION TO THE PRINCETON CLASSICS EDITION -- tPREFACE ( 1997) / rJordan, William Chester -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- tI. THE PROBLEM: PLOWDEN'S REPORTS -- tII. THE SHAKESPEARE: KING RICHARD II -- tIII. CHRIST-CENTERED KINGSHIP -- tIV. LAW-CENTERED KINGSHIP -- tV. POLITY-CENTERED KINGSHIP: CORPUS MYSTICUM -- tVI. ON CONTINUITY AND CORPORATIONS -- tVII. THE KING NEVER DIES -- tVIII. MAN-CENTERED KINGSHIP: DANTE -- tIX. EPILOGUE -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY and INDEX -- tADDENDA  aOriginally published in 1957, this classic work has guided generations of scholars through the arcane mysteries of medieval political theology. Throughout history, the notion of two bodies has permitted the post mortem continuity of monarch and monarchy, as epitomized by the statement, "The king is dead. Long live the king." In The King's Two Bodies, Ernst Kantorowicz traces the historical problem posed by the "King's two bodies"--the body natural and the body politic--back to the Middle Ages and demonstrates, by placing the concept in its proper setting of medieval thought and political theory, how the early-modern Western monarchies gradually began to develop a "political theology.?The king's natural body has physical attributes, suffers, and dies, naturally, as do all humans; but the king's other body, the spiritual body, transcends the earthly and serves as a symbol of his office as majesty with the divine right to rule. The notion of the two bodies allowed for the continuity of monarchy even when the monarch died, as summed up in the formulation "The king is dead. Long live the king." Bringing together liturgical works, images, and polemical material, The King's Two Bodies explores the long Christian past behind this "political theology." It provides a subtle history of how commonwealths developed symbolic means for establishing their sovereignty and, with such means, began to establish early forms of the nation-state. Kantorowicz fled Nazi Germany in 1938, after refusing to sign a Nazi loyalty oath, and settled in the United States. While teaching at the University of California, Berkeley, he once again refused to sign an oath of allegiance, this one designed to identify Communist Party sympathizers. He was dismissed as a result of the controversy and moved to the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, where he remained for the rest of his life, and where he wrote The King's Two Bodies.Featuring a new introduction, The King's Two Bodies is a subtle history of how commonwealths developed symbolic means for establishing their sovereignty and, with such means, began to establish early forms of the nation-state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aChurch and statexHistoryyMiddle Ages, 500-1600. 0aChurch and statezEurope. 0aKings and rulers. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh1 aJordan, William Chester.1 aLeyser, Conrad.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016z978311063859240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400880782zCo-acces